LangGraph Orchestration Details for “Don’t Quote Me”

LangGraph is the stateful orchestration engine that makes the Quote Agent reliable, controllable, and production-ready. It’s part of the LangChain ecosystem (from LangChain Inc.) and is currently one of the best tools in 2026 for building complex, multi-step AI agents.
Why LangGraph (Not Plain LangChain or Raw LLM Calls)

    Stateful — Remembers everything in a quote session (input media, draft versions, user changes, assumptions).
    Graph-based — You define the workflow as nodes + edges instead of fragile prompt chains.
    Cycles & Human-in-the-Loop — Supports loops (fine-tuning) and easy branching to human review.
    Persistence — Can save the entire graph state to Supabase so a quote can be paused and resumed.
    Observability — Excellent integration with LangSmith for debugging every step.
    Tool calling & structured output — Native, reliable support.

Core LangGraph Concepts Used Here
Concept	What It Is	How We Use It in Don’t Quote Me
Graph	Directed graph of nodes and edges	The entire quoting workflow
State	Typed object that flows between nodes (like a shared memory)	QuoteState class containing: customer info, media list, current BOM, pricing, version history, assumptions, tradie preferences
Node	A function that receives state and returns updated state	process_input, analyze_media, generate_draft, apply_user_changes, create_pdf, etc.
Edge	Conditional routing (if/else)	“If draft ready → send to user. If user asks for change → loop back. If >$5k → human review”
Persistence	Checkpointing (save state to DB)	Quote can be paused mid-chat and resumed days later
Interrupt	Pause graph for human input	Human reviewer steps in for complex jobs
